<TITLE> Police defuse bomb in communally sensitive Gujarat </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 AHMEDABAD, India, Mon Jun 1, (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Police defused a powerful bomb placed on railway tracks in a communally sensitive Gujarat on Monday, minutes after a train passed over the device. The bomb fitted with a timer was found by a security patrol in Anand station, said Ashok Kumar Mishra, a senior police officer. The bomb was timed for early morning but did not go off due to a fault in the device, Mishra said, adding a train had passed minutes before they found it. Gujarat is one of India's most communally sensitive states. Some 2,500 people, mostly Muslims, were killed there in religious rioting in 2002. The violence came after 59 Hindu pilgrims were burnt to death inside a train. The riots became a powerful recruiting tool for Islamist militants and have been often cited in emails sent to media houses after militant attacks across India in the past year. A series of 16 bombs ripped through Ahmedabad in July last year, killing 45 people and wounding more than a hun
